The mass efflux at points A and B is given by:

\begin{align*}
    (\text{Mass efflux})_A &= \rho v_A S \\
    (\text{Mass efflux})_B &= \rho v_B S
\end{align*}

The force at point A, due to the rate of change of momentum, is:

\begin{align*}
    F_A &= (\text{rate of change of momentum})_A \\
        &= \rho v_A S v_A \\
        &= \rho S v_A^2 \\
        &= \rho S (2gh) \\
        &= 2 \rho S gh
\end{align*}

The force at point B is:

\begin{align*}
    F_B &= 2 \rho S g (h + \Delta h)
\end{align*}

The difference in force, considering the vector force is in the opposite direction, is:

\begin{align*}
    F_B - F_A &= 2 \rho S g \Delta h \\
              &= 2 \times 1000 \times 1.0 \times 10^{-4} \times 9.8 \times 0.51 \\
              &= 1.0 \, \text{N}
\end{align*}

